76561198045895911,Not Recommended,259720,9671540,"Posted: 29 March, 2014",all,lisa,"I so wanted to recommend this game, especially since I've only made it through one playthrough.  However, I can't work up the desire or motivation to playthrough again for any alternate endings.All the components are there--and more.  Fading Hearts has the potential to be a really awesome game, given the variety of elements incorporated.  I just felt like there was a disconnect amongst everything, that gaming aspects and even characters were not delved into nearly enough before you reached an ending.  Why do you have to focus on one particular aspect at the expense of others?  Why are some aspects virtually worthless to develop?  Yes, I know there's supposed to be the whole replayability factor, but I find myself viewing a replay as just tedious.  I would have preferred a longer, more in-depth playthrough where all the different aspects (whether it's the rpg elements, the work, the training, the dating) were better connected and necessary.  I mean when only a handful of the manga are worth reading as far as character development. . .For me, development and disconnect were also huge problems with the characters.  I want to be immersed in a world, invested in the charaters.  I ended my first playthrough not even really caring or even knowing much of anything about the Ryou.  All the rest of the supporting cast just seemed like sidenotes on repeat.  I don't know if it's this way with every playthrough, but rather than further developing characters, conversations just kept rehashing the same things.  I learned barely anything about anyone.  In fact, I probably knew as much about Tracy, the maid at the Cosplay restaurant, as I did about the more significant characters.That development and disconnect issue carried over to the story itself.  Storylines that seemed significant at the beginning would just fizzle and disappear.  Then bam!  Here's a new shocking revelation--but there's virtually no explanation to the what, when, why, where, how questions.  But lets throw in some manga that's supposed to somehow be connected with no explanation of how it is connected, and hey, the future you (who we also have no clue as to why/what) will have a few conversations with you and disappear.Some of the other issues are related to style.  Too many typos for a professional game.  Some odd wording/odd writing.  And the black screens.  Every time you read manga, the story displays itself as weird, stencilled script across a plain, black backdrop.  And there's a lot of manga you can read.  I won't even get into the manga writing, but how can you have text only manga?So basically, when a major character apparently is killed off, and you just think ""huh"" and ""oh well,"" then go searching the internet to see if anyone can shed light on the fragmented storyline you just played through--well, it's time to find a different game."
